{
  "texts": [
    "The algorithm starts by assigning each node in the graph to a different community, then it iterates through the steps described below until there are no further changes in the network.",
    "First, for each node the algorithm will evaluate the gain of modularity when the node is moved from the current community to a neighboring one; if there's a positive gain, the node is kept in the new community.",
    "After an initial pass, this process is repeated for nodes that changed community until it reaches a local maximum, finding a partition of the graph.",
    "Secondly, the previous partition is refined by possibly further splitting some of the previously defined communities.",
    "This is done by randomly merging a node to a community if it increases modularity, which allows to further explore the partition space and avoids badly connected communities, a shortcoming from Louvain algorithm 48."
  ]
}